1
00:01:55,724 --> 00:01:59,851
Another day to live through,
better get started.

2
00:02:27,840 --> 00:02:30,633
December, 1965.

3
00:02:30,634 --> 00:02:34,303
Is that all it has been since
I inherited the world?

4
00:02:34,304 --> 00:02:36,514
Only three years.

5
00:02:37,099 --> 00:02:39,934
It seems like a hundred million.

6
00:04:43,225 --> 00:04:47,853
Yeah, I own the world.
An empty, dead, silent world.

7
00:04:57,114 --> 00:05:01,825
More of them for the pit.
Every day there are more of them.

8
00:05:01,827 --> 00:05:05,996
They live off the weak ones
and leave them for the pit.

9
00:05:47,289 --> 00:05:50,499
K-O-K-W calling. Come in.

10
00:06:04,848 --> 00:06:07,266
K-O-K-W calling.

11
00:06:07,976 --> 00:06:12,104
I'm on international
frequency. Come in.

12
00:06:45,722 --> 00:06:48,640
They can't bear to see their image.

13
00:06:48,767 --> 00:06:50,809
It repels them.

14
00:06:51,019 --> 00:06:53,270
I need more mirrors.

15
00:06:53,313 --> 00:06:56,315
And this garlic's lost its pungency.

16
00:07:09,663 --> 00:07:12,373
There was a time when
eating was pleasurable.

17
00:07:12,374 --> 00:07:16,668
Now it bores me.
Just fuel for survival.

18
00:07:16,712 --> 00:07:20,547
I'll settle for coffee and
orange juice this morning.

19
00:07:20,924 --> 00:07:26,094
But first there is my life to consider.
I'd better replace that garlic.

20
00:07:39,026 --> 00:07:43,362
I need more, lots more.
Better stop off and get them.

21
00:08:05,552 --> 00:08:10,180
I can't afford the luxury of anger.
Anger can make me vulnerable.

22
00:08:10,265 --> 00:08:15,352
It can destroy my reason, and reason
is the only advantage I have over them.

23
00:08:15,687 --> 00:08:19,022
I've got to find where
they hide during the day.

24
00:08:19,024 --> 00:08:21,483
Uncover every one of them.

25
00:08:22,110 --> 00:08:24,945
Now, where did I
finish off yesterday?

26
00:08:24,946 --> 00:08:28,282
Madison Street to 31st Avenue.

27
00:08:28,492 --> 00:08:33,120
Eleven kills over three years.

28
00:08:34,039 --> 00:08:37,958
And there's more than half
the city I haven't searched.

29
00:08:58,855 --> 00:09:00,606
They're perfect.

30
00:09:00,607 --> 00:09:05,528
Just wide enough to keep the flesh
apart so their body seal can't function.

31
00:09:05,529 --> 00:09:08,114
How many more of these
will I have to make...

32
00:09:08,115 --> 00:09:10,282
before they're all destroyed?

33
00:09:10,283 --> 00:09:14,286
They want my blood,
it's their lives or mine.

34
00:09:14,704 --> 00:09:16,830
But, I still get squeamish.

35
00:09:25,006 --> 00:09:27,883
Wait... that garlic.

36
00:09:28,343 --> 00:09:30,886
I'd better put it back
where it belongs.

37
00:09:30,887 --> 00:09:35,307
I can't live a heartbeat away
from hell and forget it.

38
00:10:20,353 --> 00:10:24,731
I'm out of gas. That means one
more stop I'll have to make.

39
00:10:46,713 --> 00:10:49,089
I can get rid of them later.

40
00:10:49,090 --> 00:10:51,717
Right now, I'm out of gas.

41
00:14:12,961 --> 00:14:14,837
They're still fresh.

42
00:14:14,838 --> 00:14:18,590
But I'll take only what I need.
They've got to last.

43
00:14:51,541 --> 00:14:55,002
They can wait too.
I've got my life to worry about.

44
00:14:55,003 --> 00:14:58,421
Those mirrors have to be
replaced before dark.

45
00:15:29,162 --> 00:15:33,624
Square blocks to search.
How many of them still exist?

46
00:15:33,625 --> 00:15:36,918
How long will I have to
keep up this search?

47
00:16:42,819 --> 00:16:47,072
I haven't much time left.
It'll be dark in an hour.

48
00:17:35,830 --> 00:17:40,792
And now 12 long hours
before the sun will rise...

49
00:17:40,793 --> 00:17:44,295
and drive them back to darkness.

50
00:18:25,421 --> 00:18:28,715
Morgan, come out.

51
00:18:29,175 --> 00:18:31,092
Come out.

52
00:18:43,940 --> 00:18:49,777
Morgan, come out. Come out.

53
00:19:32,363 --> 00:19:34,697
Robert, help me!

54
00:19:47,545 --> 00:19:49,420
Another day.

55
00:19:49,630 --> 00:19:53,091
Another day to start all over again.

56
00:22:29,457 --> 00:22:31,082
Virge.

57
00:22:33,169 --> 00:22:35,169
Virge.

58
00:22:35,796 --> 00:22:38,464
God, how I miss you.

59
00:23:09,956 --> 00:23:13,666
The sun's already set.
They'll be everywhere!

60
00:24:21,736 --> 00:24:24,695
It's Morgan. Get him!

61
00:25:31,597 --> 00:25:33,681
Do you hear?

62
00:27:55,991 --> 00:27:58,200
Morgan.

63
00:27:59,703 --> 00:28:02,246
Do you hear, Morgan?

64
00:28:02,748 --> 00:28:04,248
Morgan.

65
00:28:05,251 --> 00:28:07,543
Do you hear, Morgan?

66
00:28:09,922 --> 00:28:12,173
Three years.

67
00:28:14,593 --> 00:28:17,970
Three years.

68
00:28:33,988 --> 00:28:38,199
One, two, three, four,
five, six, seven.

69
00:28:39,159 --> 00:28:40,535
Hey, Virge? Virge?

70
00:28:40,536 --> 00:28:44,872
Yes? Oh no! My makeup. My hair!

71
00:28:46,417 --> 00:28:48,068
Hey, where is everybody?

72
00:28:48,069 --> 00:28:50,044
- All I can see is...
- Hi, Ben!

73
00:28:50,045 --> 00:28:53,214
I can hear children,
but I can't see any children.

74
00:28:53,215 --> 00:28:55,049
Uncle Ben!

75
00:28:56,010 --> 00:28:58,135
Uncle Ben!

76
00:28:58,596 --> 00:29:00,805
Look at Uncle Ben!

77
00:29:01,181 --> 00:29:04,266
Ben! Uncle Ben! Uncle Ben!

78
00:29:08,105 --> 00:29:11,232
- What did you bring me?
- Open them and see.

79
00:29:11,233 --> 00:29:14,026
- Come. Come.
- Go on and open them Kathy.

80
00:29:27,875 --> 00:29:30,126
Take a look at this.

81
00:29:41,096 --> 00:29:44,557
- It's highly theoretical, Ben.
- Theoretical?

82
00:29:45,476 --> 00:29:49,937
Do I have to remind you that theory
is the beginning of solution?

83
00:29:55,319 --> 00:29:59,738
"Is Europe's disease carried
on the wind?" Is it, Ben?

84
00:30:00,407 --> 00:30:03,450
- It could be.
- And if it is?

85
00:30:03,869 --> 00:30:05,953
It isn't, Virge.

86
00:30:06,246 --> 00:30:09,290
Is that what you really think,
or just what you'd like to think?

87
00:30:09,291 --> 00:30:13,211
I cannot accept half-baked
theories that sell newspapers.

88
00:30:13,212 --> 00:30:16,422
I'm a scientist, not an alarmist.

89
00:30:16,423 --> 00:30:18,424
You're whistling past the graveyard.

90
00:30:18,425 --> 00:30:21,344
Is that a commentary
on my work at the lab?

91
00:30:21,345 --> 00:30:24,389
- We both know how hard you've worked.
- I'm sorry, Ben.

92
00:30:24,390 --> 00:30:28,726
I just can't accept the
idea of universal disease.

93
00:30:29,895 --> 00:30:33,022
Uncle Ben, you promised
us card tricks.

94
00:30:33,023 --> 00:30:36,567
All right, Kathy.
Who can resist that face?

95
00:30:37,403 --> 00:30:41,071
All right. Card tricks. Card tricks.

96
00:30:43,158 --> 00:30:44,783
Robert...

97
00:30:44,785 --> 00:30:48,704
Is it possible this germ,
or virus, could be airborne?

98
00:30:50,124 --> 00:30:52,750
Anything is possible, Virge.

99
00:30:52,876 --> 00:30:56,963
The best brains in the world have
been running through this thing...

100
00:30:56,964 --> 00:30:58,673
with a fine-toothed comb.

101
00:30:58,674 --> 00:31:00,883
The germ is visible
under a microscope...

102
00:31:00,884 --> 00:31:04,303
but it's not like any
bacilli I've ever known.

103
00:31:05,013 --> 00:31:06,639
In what way?

104
00:31:06,640 --> 00:31:11,060
It can't be destroyed by any process
we've been able to uncover.

105
00:31:11,645 --> 00:31:15,773
But with the whole world trying,
there must be a solution.

106
00:31:16,275 --> 00:31:19,443
Mommy, when are we
gonna cut the cake?

107
00:31:20,738 --> 00:31:24,031
Right now our problem
is to cut that cake.

108
00:31:25,409 --> 00:31:29,870
- Hey, Mommy. Mommy!
- Coming. Coming.

109
00:32:54,706 --> 00:32:56,958
The wind wake you up?

110
00:32:56,959 --> 00:32:58,918
It always does.

111
00:32:58,919 --> 00:33:01,688
- How do you feel?
- I'm all right.

112
00:33:01,689 --> 00:33:04,866
- Don't get up, honey.
- I'm not sick, Bob.

113
00:33:04,867 --> 00:33:07,343
- I'll make your breakfast.
- You don't have to.

114
00:33:07,344 --> 00:33:10,513
I'll be all right.
Go on and read your paper.

115
00:33:10,514 --> 00:33:12,264
All right.

116
00:33:54,808 --> 00:33:58,102
Sweetheart, look, if you don't
feel well, please go back to bed.

117
00:33:58,103 --> 00:34:01,063
I'm just a little tired, that's all.

118
00:34:01,732 --> 00:34:04,733
I wish somebody would find a vaccine.

119
00:34:05,402 --> 00:34:08,445
It's all we're working
on at the lab, Virge.

120
00:34:09,197 --> 00:34:12,616
Maybe you better not send
her to school today.

121
00:34:13,869 --> 00:34:15,702
All right.

122
00:34:16,413 --> 00:34:20,040
- Do you think you should go to work?
- I have to.

123
00:34:20,083 --> 00:34:22,042
Bob?

124
00:34:22,085 --> 00:34:25,712
Bob, I'm so frightened.

125
00:34:26,882 --> 00:34:30,426
Everything's going to be
all right, sweetheart.

126
00:35:01,833 --> 00:35:05,043
- Well?
- The bacilli are multiplying.

127
00:35:05,545 --> 00:35:08,381
That kicks the bone marrow
theory in the head.

128
00:35:08,382 --> 00:35:10,716
This specimen shows a
higher white count...

129
00:35:10,717 --> 00:35:13,469
than when I put it on the slide.

130
00:35:13,720 --> 00:35:17,848
Those cells are still living,
Dr. Mercer, off one another.

131
00:35:18,517 --> 00:35:20,559
There has to be an answer.

132
00:35:20,560 --> 00:35:24,105
You've heard that all communications are
ended outside the continental limits?

133
00:35:24,106 --> 00:35:25,398
Yes, I heard.

134
00:35:25,399 --> 00:35:29,693
That leaves it in our laps.
So we keep trying. Where's Cortman?

135
00:35:30,028 --> 00:35:32,238
Well he should be here by now.

136
00:35:32,239 --> 00:35:35,783
You two stay on this virus theory
until I decide it's exhausted.

137
00:35:35,784 --> 00:35:37,326
Right.

138
00:35:38,495 --> 00:35:40,997
- Yes, sir?
- Morgan will fill you in.

139
00:35:40,998 --> 00:35:42,915
All right, sir.

140
00:35:44,960 --> 00:35:49,281
And what did the great man of science
have to say today? More of the usual?

141
00:35:49,282 --> 00:35:52,133
Oh, he's trying, Ben.
Just like the rest of us.

142
00:35:52,134 --> 00:35:54,218
And nothing works.

143
00:35:54,386 --> 00:35:57,138
The streets are swarming
with truckloads of bodies...

144
00:35:57,139 --> 00:35:59,974
that they're throwing
into that God-awful pit.

145
00:35:59,975 --> 00:36:01,892
And the dedicated
Dr. Mercer goes on...

146
00:36:01,893 --> 00:36:04,770
with his plodding,
unimaginative approach.

147
00:36:04,771 --> 00:36:07,732
- You have a better idea?
- Maybe.

148
00:36:07,733 --> 00:36:11,485
- At least it involves imagination.
- Ben, it's as simple as this.

149
00:36:11,486 --> 00:36:14,697
An unknown germ is being
blown around the world.

150
00:36:14,698 --> 00:36:18,242
It's highly contagious,
and it's reached plague proportions.

151
00:36:18,243 --> 00:36:21,787
And you don't believe some
of the dead have come back?

152
00:36:21,788 --> 00:36:23,914
Let's get to work.

153
00:36:25,709 --> 00:36:29,670
And why are they burning the bodies?
Why don't they bury them?

154
00:36:29,671 --> 00:36:32,673
Because it's the best known way
to control the contagion...

155
00:36:32,674 --> 00:36:34,717
to keep the germ from spreading.

156
00:36:34,718 --> 00:36:37,386
That's what we've always
believed, at any rate.

157
00:36:37,387 --> 00:36:41,598
- You'd prefer us to believe in vampires?
- If they exist, yes.

158
00:36:42,225 --> 00:36:44,685
There are stories being told, Bob.

159
00:36:44,686 --> 00:36:47,855
By people who are out of
their minds with fear!

160
00:36:47,856 --> 00:36:52,234
Maybe, but there are too many
to be just coincidental.

161
00:36:53,236 --> 00:36:57,864
Stories about people who have
died, and have come back.

162
00:36:57,949 --> 00:37:00,034
They're stories, Ben, stories.

163
00:37:00,035 --> 00:37:04,371
And why are the infected people
always so tired in the daytime?

164
00:37:04,372 --> 00:37:07,124
Why can't they stand the sunlight?

165
00:37:07,125 --> 00:37:09,918
Why are they only seen at night?

166
00:37:11,338 --> 00:37:13,130
Come here.

167
00:37:15,717 --> 00:37:17,510
- Look.
- I know as well as...

168
00:37:17,511 --> 00:37:18,635
Look!

169
00:37:21,681 --> 00:37:24,683
- Now, is this bacilli or isn't it?
- It doesn't alter...

170
00:37:24,684 --> 00:37:29,105
And this bacilli is found in the blood
of every infected person, or isn't it?

171
00:37:29,106 --> 00:37:32,358
To show me germs is not to
refute these stories, Bob.

172
00:37:32,359 --> 00:37:36,903
The point is, if there are vampires,
they exist in spite of these germs.

173
00:37:37,072 --> 00:37:39,656
Come on, let's get to work.

174
00:37:47,999 --> 00:37:49,792
Until further notice this station...

175
00:37:49,793 --> 00:37:53,838
will continue its around-the-clock
coverage of this national disaster.

176
00:37:53,839 --> 00:37:57,299
And now we switch you
to the state capitol...

177
00:37:57,300 --> 00:38:00,136
where His Excellency, the Governor

178
00:38:00,137 --> 00:38:03,305
is speaking from the
executive mansion.

179
00:38:04,141 --> 00:38:08,102
Further, I have in conjunction
with the Federal Government...

180
00:38:08,103 --> 00:38:11,313
declared this state to
be a disaster area.

181
00:38:11,314 --> 00:38:15,234
The public health is dependent on the
bodies of the deceased being burned.

182
00:38:15,235 --> 00:38:17,820
You must notify the Health
Department immediately...

183
00:38:17,821 --> 00:38:19,864
if you have a plague
victim in your home.

184
00:38:19,865 --> 00:38:22,491
Under no circumstances
should you gather publicly.

185
00:38:22,492 --> 00:38:25,535
In view of the dire emergency
that exists, I intend to...

186
00:38:30,834 --> 00:38:32,793
Anything new?

187
00:38:33,628 --> 00:38:35,671
No, nothing new.

188
00:38:44,514 --> 00:38:46,181
Nothing.

189
00:38:52,689 --> 00:38:54,898
Mommy, where are you?

190
00:38:56,276 --> 00:38:58,568
Mommy, I can't see.

191
00:38:59,279 --> 00:39:00,737
Mommy...

192
00:39:02,073 --> 00:39:05,325
- I'm going to call the doctor.
- I said no.

193
00:39:09,039 --> 00:39:11,916
Virge, there's nothing they can do.

194
00:39:11,917 --> 00:39:16,420
- But we can't just let her lie there.
- Well, this way she has a chance.

195
00:39:16,421 --> 00:39:20,674
If you call a doctor, he'll report it.
Do you want that?

196
00:39:26,056 --> 00:39:28,098
Mommy, help me.

197
00:39:28,266 --> 00:39:30,100
Mommy...

198
00:39:30,727 --> 00:39:32,811
Mommy, please help me.

199
00:39:33,146 --> 00:39:34,771
Mommy, help me.

200
00:39:35,899 --> 00:39:40,152
- How can you be so sure she's...
- Blindness is one of the symptoms.

201
00:39:40,904 --> 00:39:44,531
You're not to call a doctor
under any circumstances.

202
00:39:44,532 --> 00:39:48,368
No one is to come into this house.
Now remember that.

203
00:39:48,703 --> 00:39:51,913
Mommy... Mommy...

204
00:39:52,832 --> 00:39:55,208
Mommy, where are you?

205
00:39:56,670 --> 00:40:01,465
I've got to pick Ben Cortman
up on the way to the lab.

206
00:40:02,217 --> 00:40:05,135
No one is to come into this house.

207
00:40:05,387 --> 00:40:07,512
Now remember that!

208
00:40:22,487 --> 00:40:26,198
No! No! No! Please!

209
00:40:29,369 --> 00:40:32,662
Please don't let him
be buried in the pit.

210
00:40:33,540 --> 00:40:37,584
Please, for God's sake.
Don't take him away like this.

211
00:40:37,585 --> 00:40:40,420
You can't! You can't!

212
00:41:15,790 --> 00:41:19,501
- Who's there?
- It's me, Ben. We're late.

213
00:41:25,759 --> 00:41:28,593
Ben, what's the matter with you?

214
00:41:28,636 --> 00:41:31,096
Nothing. And I'm going
to keep it that way.

215
00:41:31,097 --> 00:41:35,642
- Ben! Look, let's talk about this.
- There's nothing to talk about.

216
00:41:36,478 --> 00:41:40,772
You think I'm out of my mind.
You laughed at me and my theory.

217
00:41:41,399 --> 00:41:42,983
You might be one of them.

218
00:41:42,984 --> 00:41:45,235
Ben, look, you're ill.
You ought to see a doctor.

219
00:41:45,236 --> 00:41:47,070
No doctors.

220
00:41:47,113 --> 00:41:50,407
You take care of your life.
I'll take care of mine.

221
00:41:50,408 --> 00:41:52,701
Now get away from here.

222
00:41:52,786 --> 00:41:55,662
You understand? Get away from here!

223
00:43:11,197 --> 00:43:15,033
If you're looking for
anybody but me, forget it.

224
00:43:21,416 --> 00:43:24,626
- Are they all gone?
- That's right.

225
00:43:24,627 --> 00:43:27,921
Is there any hope from
the latest reports?

226
00:43:27,922 --> 00:43:30,173
No, not yet.

227
00:43:30,884 --> 00:43:33,760
But believe me, Morgan,
we'll find an answer.

228
00:43:33,761 --> 00:43:37,263
When, Doctor?
We need it right now. I need it!

229
00:43:37,932 --> 00:43:41,810
You're the only one who wasn't
afraid to come here today.

230
00:43:41,811 --> 00:43:44,771
What's going to happen, Dr. Mercer?

231
00:43:45,356 --> 00:43:49,776
Is everybody in the world going to die
before someone finds the answer?

232
00:43:49,777 --> 00:43:52,028
No, I don't think so.

233
00:43:52,780 --> 00:43:57,826
I don't deny that there's some strange
evolutionary process going on.

234
00:43:58,369 --> 00:44:01,162
But mankind won't be destroyed.

235
00:44:01,206 --> 00:44:04,874
The fact that you and I
are working here today...

236
00:44:05,376 --> 00:44:07,585
is evidence of that.

237
00:44:26,523 --> 00:44:28,732
All right. Let's roll.

238
00:45:03,184 --> 00:45:04,768
When?

239
00:45:05,895 --> 00:45:07,187
When?

240
00:45:07,188 --> 00:45:09,356
I called a doctor. I had to.

241
00:45:09,357 --> 00:45:11,900
I told you not to call anyone.

242
00:45:11,901 --> 00:45:14,819
Bob, she was blind.

243
00:45:15,029 --> 00:45:17,030
She couldn't see.

244
00:45:17,031 --> 00:45:20,867
She kept reaching out her
hands, and groping for me.

245
00:45:21,744 --> 00:45:26,498
And all of a sudden she was gone.

246
00:45:28,668 --> 00:45:30,627
And they came...

247
00:45:30,628 --> 00:45:33,714
and I tried to stop them.
They took her.

248
00:45:33,715 --> 00:45:36,174
I saw a truck out there.

249
00:45:37,093 --> 00:45:39,761
Was that it? Was it?

250
00:45:39,762 --> 00:45:41,346
Yes.

251
00:45:53,860 --> 00:45:56,945
I'm sorry, lady.
There's nothing I can do.

252
00:45:56,946 --> 00:45:59,990
Let that truck through.
Get out of the way.

253
00:45:59,991 --> 00:46:03,326
Get back, folks.
Nobody's allowed out there.

254
00:46:03,745 --> 00:46:06,997
Please, all of you.
Get behind those lines.

255
00:46:06,998 --> 00:46:10,333
Look sharp there. Move. Move along.

256
00:46:12,629 --> 00:46:16,214
Make way for that truck. This way.

257
00:46:18,801 --> 00:46:21,970
Hey, you, mister! Come back!

258
00:46:33,149 --> 00:46:36,026
Did this truck just come
in from Market Street?

259
00:46:36,027 --> 00:46:38,904
I said, did this truck just
come in from Market Street?

260
00:46:38,905 --> 00:46:41,156
Mister, I don't know.

261
00:46:56,255 --> 00:46:59,424
Hey, you don't
belong in here. Get out.

262
00:47:00,426 --> 00:47:03,011
- I said get out!
- I want my daughter.

263
00:47:03,012 --> 00:47:06,681
Mister, a lot of daughters are
in there, including my own.

264
00:47:44,303 --> 00:47:46,596
Bob, I can't see!

265
00:47:46,723 --> 00:47:48,598
I can't see!

266
00:47:51,060 --> 00:47:52,352
Virge!

267
00:48:16,794 --> 00:48:18,795
Virge.

268
00:48:40,067 --> 00:48:41,651
No.

269
00:48:42,695 --> 00:48:45,822
I won't let them put
you there, Virge.

270
00:48:46,908 --> 00:48:48,741
I promise.

271
00:48:50,036 --> 00:48:52,787
I won't let them put you there.

272
00:50:52,783 --> 00:50:55,118
Let me in.

273
00:50:58,789 --> 00:51:01,332
Let me in.

